    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-02-02T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-02-02T14:00:00-05:00" n="434"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d434">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">721.23/953: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clark</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico City</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-02-02T13:00:00-06:00"
                            >February 2, 1933—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>24. Referring to Department’s circular telegram February 1, 7 p.m., 1933.
                    Notwithstanding Mexico has no diplomatic relations with Peru (see my telegram
                    90, May 25, 7 p.m., and Department’s instruction 671, May 28, 1932<note n="79"
                        xml:id="d434fn79">Neither printed.</note>) I discreetly interviewed the
                    Minister of Foreign Affairs this morning, who confirmed the impression I
                    previously had, that owing to the fact that Mexico has no diplomatic relations
                    with Peru it is not possible for Mexico to make any representations to Peru on
                    this matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clark</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
